properties.description:
Western Ridge & Homestead Creek Geotrail
Geotrail Name Western Ridge & Homestead Creek Geotrail
State or Territory NSW
Indigenous Country Pantjikali, Malyankapa
Georegion <Null>
Detailed Description From west to east, you’ll travel down through the Devonian sequence from youngest to oldest rocks. Starting at the Homestead Creek Camping Ground follow the Western Ridge walking track (stops 1–2), best done when the sun is setting over the desert plains, this section of the geotrail is 3 km return (1.5 hours). Next day, take the walking track to Thaaklatjika/Wright’s Cave (stops 3–5, accessible by wheelchair), then the walking track along Homestead Creek and around the Rockholes Loop (stops 6–11). Overall distance returning along the same track is 6 km (2.5–3.5 hours). Alternatively, you can continue along the Homestead Gorge track and return along the Bynguano Range walking track, allow 4–6 hours in total and ensure you carry sufficient water.
Geological Age Early – Middle Devonian
Trail Length (km) 9.5
Key Features Western Ridge, Thaaklatjika (Wright’s Cave), Homestead Gorge, Aboriginal engravings and artwork

Flora The Mutawintji Lands are typically semi-arid or arid, so climatic conditions have a big effect on plant species distribution and growth. If you are fortunate enough to see Mutawintji in times of good seasonal rainfall, you will see an abundance of plant species in many different habitats. Deep rocky gorges and sheltered areas are generally a refuge for plant species since they trap or preserve moisture. Mutawintji is also nationally recognised as a refuge for many unique vegetations types. The main types of plant communities include mulga shrublands, saltbush or bluebush (Chenopod) shrublands, arid woodlands and woody shrublands. You’ll also notice corridors of river red gum woodlands along drainage lines and creeklines.
Fauna Mutawintji teems with the wildlife that has occupied these lands since ancient times. You might see a wedge-tailed eagle or even a peregrine falcon and enjoy the chatter of noisy short-billed correllas, zebra finches, budgerigars, apostle birds and magpies. Crossing your path may be goannas and snakes, and look out for members of the only colony in NSW of the endangered yellow-footed rock wallaby. The largest of the rock-wallabies, it is Australia's most brightly coloured mammal – look for them on rocky ridges in the park.
Indigineous Culture Mutawintji National Park is within the tribal lands of the Pantjikali and Malyankapa people. The national park protects a ceremonial centre for Aboriginal people from a wide region and contains important features such as creation places, rock engravings, stencils, paintings and evidence of past occupation. Mutawintji Historic Site was where initiations, rain-making and other ceremonies were once held, attracting over 1,000 people. Today Aboriginal people from around the region continue to gather here for cultural purposes and meetings. Significant places nearby include Nuntherungie, Gnalta, Yancannia, Cobham Lake, Koonenberry Mountain, Poolamacca and Mount Arrowsmith.

Simple Description Enjoy amazing views of desert plains from beginning of this walk, which follows a small part of the Western Ridge walking track and is best done at sunset. Later explore the spectacular scenery, Aboriginal art and craggy cliffs along Homestead Gorge before climbing up to see waterholes on the Rockholes Loop.

properties.Name: Mutawintji Historic Site Geotrail
properties.description:
Mutawintji Historic Site Geotrail
Geotrail Name Mutawintji Historic Site Geotrail
State or Territory NSW
Indigenous Country Pantjikali, Malyankapa
Georegion <Null>
Detailed Description Mutawintji Historic Site and Old Coach Road drive (stops 14–16) Humans have been in this area for many thousands of years, drawn to the abundant resources. The north-south valley forms a corridor that continues to be used and the surrounding gorges provide water that has sustained ongoing occupation. Mutawintji Historic Site (Stop 14) is a very special ceremonial place and now preserves superb Aboriginal artwork, along with a unique fossil site with 400 million year old footprints! Note that Stop 14 can only be accessed with an authorised guide as part of a pre-booked 2 hour tour. Mutawintji Historic Site has a gated and locked road access. The guides will lead you to the visitor centre for the Mutawintji Historic Site where informative presentations and displays on the cultural history of Mutawintji are shared. Visitor vehicles are parked at the centre. The guides will then take you on a walking tour of culturally significant places nearby. Stops 15 and 16 are accessible alongside the Old Coach Road on the way to the Historic Site, driving northward from the main campsite. Overall distance (including guided tour) 3 km return (3‒3.5 hours).
Geological Age Early – Middle Devonian
Trail Length (km) 3
Key Features Aboriginal engravings and artwork, fossilised prehistoric animal tracks

non-Indigenous Culture Over 100 years ago the pub and coach stop here were popular with miners and station workers. Old Coach Road was the major route between Broken Hill and White Cliffs in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Cobb & Co ran a weekly stagecoach mail service between the recently opened mining towns – a rough and bumpy 4 day trip. Dances were held at the pub and Boxing Day races were held nearby, at what is now the airstrip. The first Rockholes Hotel was a temporary shanty constructed by Charles Raven in the 1890s to provide refreshments for tired travellers. In 1905 it was replaced by a building of wood, hessian cloth and iron. This building burned down in 1915 and was replaced in 1916 by a building constructed from surrounding sandstone of the Old Coach Road Formation, with a cool underground dining room!

Simple Description Linking Mutawintji Historic Site and the surrounding area, these sites look at human interaction with the landscape over thousands of years. As well as superb Aboriginal artwork and colonial sites, you’ll see unique evidence of creatures walking over the landscape around 400 million years ago.

properties.Name: Mutawintji Split Rock Geotrail
properties.description:
Mutawintji Split Rock Geotrail
Geotrail Name Mutawintji Split Rock Geotrail
State or Territory NSW
Indigenous Country Pantjikali, Malyankapa
Georegion <Null>
Detailed Description Starting at the Coach Road drive carpark, you'll walk over broad, undulating river deposits between distant rocky ridges such as spectacular Wana Karnu (Boomerang Rock). At the end of the walk you’ll see massive rocks that have been moved and shaped by faulting during mountain-building events hundreds of millions of years ago, forming a culturally significant place. The Aboriginal Owners of Mutawintji advise Split Rock is a site that has significance for women. Cultural protocols request that whilst the walk towards Split Rock is suitable for men and women, that only women enter the last 100m space around Split Rock.
Geological Age Early – Middle Devonian
Trail Length (km) 6
Key Features Boomerang Rock, Split Rock

non-Indigenous Culture Near Split Rock are the remains of a small hut made of cypress pine which was once the home of a notorious bushranger. He had sweeping views of the coach road and would climb down to rob travellers between White Cliffs and Broken Hill of their gold and opal. One day there was a shootout with a coach’s armed escorts, leaving bullet holes in the hut’s timbers as a reminder of conflict over 100 years ago. In fireplaces left around the hut, archaeologists have uncovered an array of his victims’ belongings such as belt buckles, buttons and clay pipes.
